abstract: MINNEAPOLIS, Nov. 30. -- By the testimony given to-day by R.J. abstract: The final football game of the season for 1906 will be played this afternoon on Franklin Field, Philadelphia, between teams representing the Naval Academy and West Point, two of the most important branches of the United States service. abstract: LONDON, Dec. 1 -- The financial situation in London has greatly improved this week. The Bank of England has increased its reserve by 2,249,000, so that it now amounts to 23,613,000, which is 321,000 more than it held a year ago. This improvement in the Bank's condition has been followed by a weakening in the rates for money, which are now the best in three months.

abstract: CHICAGO, Dec. 12. -- The American Baseball League is a united and happy family once more. For the past year Ban Johnson, President of the League, and Charles Cominskey have been at loggerheads, and their differences have threatened to spread dissention among the other members of the organization. To-day, at the annual meeting of the League, these two men became reconciled and have renewed the close friendship which existed for so many years between them.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Dec. 12. -- The increased cost of living in Washington has led to a demand on the part of almost everybody on a Government payroll to have his pay raised this session. abstract: EAST WILLISTON, L.I., Dec. 14. -- While ten persons slept soundly in the home of Charles Oakley, Sr., a wealthy retired farmer, on the Westbury Road, early to-day, burglars got through the front door by picking the lock. abstract: PHILADELPHIA, Dec. 14. -- There is a mystery as to the whereabouts of Ida Miller, heir to $200,000 left by her father. abstract: KINGSTON, Jamaica, Dec. 17. -- The Hamburg-American Line tourist steamer Prinzessin Victoria Luise, from New York Dec. 12 for this port, went ashore last night on the rocks under the lighthouse off Port Royal while on her way back to New York. abstract: WASHINGTON, Dec. 20. -- Speaker Cannon to-day passed by the luxurious and be-tableclothed House restaurant for Congressmen to the bare-floored little alleyway, with little naked tables of the Beefstead John sort, where the plebeian multitude are unceremoniously fed by hoarse and jostling waiters. Every waiter in sight stood transfixed, and three dropped laden plates with sonorous crashes.

abstract: PARIS, Dec. 23. -- The market was depressed in the early days of last week on account of the critical monetary situation abroad, which necessarily was reflected here. abstract: FREEPORT, L.I., Dec. 23. -- The home of Mathew T. abstract: One of the minor money movements of the year, which, though generally unnoticed, is well worth reckoning, is the flood of remittances sent home for Christmas by our foreign-born population. abstract: Francis W. Greene, Jr., of Jamaica, has a goat of the Bill kind. The goat will eat out of your hand or an ash can or garbage pail, but his chief delight, aside from the consumption of nails, tomato cans, iron fences, and other tidbits, is war. Strife is the breath of life to Billy. Bloodshed, his own or another's, is his delight.

abstract: LONDON, Dec. 26. -- Christmas of 1906 will be memorable for the heaviest snowstorms the United Kingdom has experienced in many years. In the southern counties of England and in Scotland the snow was accompanied by heavy gales. There was an average fall of from four to six inches, which drifted badly and worked serious hindrance to locomotion of all kinds and inconvenience to holidaymakers.

abstract: BELGRADE, Servia, Dec. 27. -- King Peter signed the Loan bill to-day. When the Deputies left the Chamber after the passage of the bill, there was a serious student demonstration against the Government and the dynasty, which had to be suppressed by gendarmes. There was much resentment among the students because of a rumor that King Peter intended to give $600,000 out of the loan as a dowry to his daughter, Princess Helene.

abstract: ROCHESTER, N.Y., Dec. 27. -- Secretary of State-elect John S. Whalen announced his appointments to-night from a sick bed at his home on Frank Street. He is suffering from a severe cold, but his physician, Dr. Urquhart, believes he will be able to attend the inauguration. With one exception, Mr. Whalen, who made the canvass for his office as a distinctive union labor candidate, has appointed labor men of State reputation.

abstract: FRESNO, Cal., Dec. 30. -- A jury in the case of Willard Zibbell against the Southern Pacific Company, gave a judgment yesterday against the railroad of $100,000 for personal injuries. In July, 1905, Zibbell, who is a race horse driver, was struck by a box car moving in the freight yards without a light, and he lost his left arm, right hand, left leg, and right foot.

abstract: PARIS, Dec. 30. -- The activity of the Bourse last week was confined to the Russian group and Rio Tintos. The latter fluctuated wildly, and although most of the sensational advance was retained, the record price of 2,300f. could not be kept up. The present position of the copper market strengthens the belief that the Rio Tinto Company will continue to make large profits, and a further increase in dividends is predicted.
